{"id":"1912.13138","submitter":"Brett Lopez","authors":"Brett T. Lopez and Jean-Jacques E. Slotine","title":"Contraction Metrics in Adaptive Nonlinear Control","comments":"Added transient bounds for matched uncertainty and results with\n  parameter bounds. Improved stability proof","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"eess.SY cs.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Lyapunov stability theory is the bedrock of direct adaptive control.\nFundamentally, Lyapunov stability requires constructing a distance-like\nfunction which must decrease with time to ensure stability. Feedback\nlinearization, backstepping, and sum-of-squares optimization are common\napproaches for constructing such a distance function, but require the system to\npossess certain inherent/structural properties or involves solving a non-convex\noptimization problem. These restrictions/complexities arise because Lyapunov\nstability theory relies on constructing an explicit distance function. This\nwork uses contraction metrics to derive an adaptive controller for stabilizable\nnonlinear systems by constructing a distance-like function differentially\nrather than explicitly. Because stabilizability is in fact equivalent to the\nexistence of a contraction metric, the proposed approach is significantly more\ngeneral than available results in the literature. In particular, the method can\nbe applied to underactuated systems. More broadly, it can also be used in\ntransfer learning where a feedback controller has been carefully learned for a\nnominal system, but needs to remain effective in the presence of significant\nbut structured variations in parameters. Simulation results illustrate the\napproach.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 Dec 2019 01:49:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 17 Feb 2020 06:18:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-02-18"}
